0
\end{array}\right),
\]

\end_inset

 with these cycles intertwined by 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the 3D lattice of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{A}_{3}$
\end_inset

 root system generated by the 12 root vectors which are coordinate permutations
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $(6,-6,0,0)^{T}$
\end_inset

.
 (The factor of 6 in the coordinates ensures that all relevant points have
 integer coordinates.) In 3D, the corresponding points are 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
 & (0,\pm6,\pm6)^{T},\\
 & (\pm6,0,\pm6)^{T},\\
 & (\pm6,\pm6,0)^{T},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 which are the edge midpoints of a cube, and comprise the vertices of a
 cuboctahedron.
 The generated lattice is characterized by the individual coordinates being
 divisible by 6 and the sum of coordinates divisible by 12.
 We need to consider offsets by 
\begin_inset Formula $(-3,-3,-3)^{T}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus the individual coordinates are 3 mod 6, and the sum of coordinates
 is 3 mod 12.
 The four offsets adjacent to 
\begin_inset Formula $(0,0,0)^{T}$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $(-3,-3,-3)^{T}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $(-3,3,3)^{T}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $(3,-3,3)^{T}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $(3,3,-3)^{T}$
\end_inset

.
 These points are barycenters of four tetrahedra, corresponding to four
 of the eight triangular faces of the cuboctahedron.
 (An alternative possible system of offsets is those by 
\begin_inset Formula $(3,3,3)$
\end_inset

.) Coordination sequence is A008253.
\end_layout

